definition.value: A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 7-hydroxybacteriochlorophyllide c; major species at pH 7.3.

A hydroxycalciol that consists of vitamin D3 (calciol) bearing additional hydroxy substituents at positions 1, 23 and 25 (with 1alpha,23S-configuration). An intermediate in the degradation pathway of 1alpha,25-(OH)2D3.
A lipid A derivative, prepared from Campylobacter jejuni HS:19, in which each of its two glucosaminyl units is substituted on nitrogen by a 3-(2-hydroxytetracosanoyloxy)octadecanoyl unit.
A quaternary ammonium salt composed of 3-{[cyclopentyl(hydroxy)phenylacetyl]oxy}-1,1-dimethylpyrrolidin-1-ium and  bromide ions in a 1:1 ratio.
A glycopyrronium bromide that has (2S,3R)-configuration. The racemate, ritropirronium bromide, is used for treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
A glycopyrronium bromide that has (2R,3S)-configuration. The racemate, ritropirronium bromide, is used for treatment of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from O(4)-(N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl)-trans-4-hydroxy-L-proline.
A member of the class of lipoxins that is lipoxin A4 carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.
A lipooligosaccharide, prepared from Campylobacter jejuni (strain HS:19). It binds with cholera toxin B.
A member of the class of lipoxins that is lipoxin B4 carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.
A DiHETE that is 5-HETE carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.

A hydroxycalciol that is 25-hydroxyvitamin D3 carrying an additional hydroxy group at position 23 (with 23S-configuration) and an oxo group at position 24. An intermediate in the degradation pathway of 25-OH-vitamin D3.

A tetrasaccharide glycosyl group consisting of beta-D-galactosyl, beta-D-N-acetyl-galactosaminyl and D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->4), to the D-galactosyl residue at the reducing end is also linked (2->3) an N-acetyl-alpha-neuraminyl residue.
A DiHETE that is 8-HETE carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.
A hydroxycalciol that consists of vitamin D3 (calciol) carrying an additional hydroxy group at position 20 with S-configuration.
A hydroxycalciol that consists of vitamin D3 (calciol) carrying additional hydroxy groups  at positions 20 (with S-configuration) and 25.
A hydroxycalciol that consists of vitamin D3 (calciol) carrying additional hydroxy groups at positions 20 (with S-configuration) and 24 (with R-configuration).
A hydroxycalciol that consists of vitamin D3 (calciol) carrying additional hydroxy groups at positions 20 and 24 (both with S-configuration).
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and carboxy groups of 3-deoxy-D-glycero-beta-D-galacto-nonulosonic acid 9-phosphate
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of 3-deoxy-D-glycero-beta-D-galacto-nonulosonic acid
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid and phosphate functions of CMP-3-deoxy-D-glycero-beta-D-galacto-nonulosonic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A DiHETE that is 12-HETE carrying an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.
A compound that enhances the activity of a steroid receptor coactivator.
A member of the class of leukotrienes that is 6-trans-leukotriene B4 bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at position 20.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is MgADP which has lost the proton attached to the diphosphate moiety.
A member of the class of biphenyls that is benzidine in which one of the hydrogens ortho to each of the amino groups has been replaced by an amino group.
A HETrE that is (8Z,10E,14Z)-icosatrienoic acid in which the hydroxy group is located at the 12(S)-posiiton.
A 12-HPEPE in which the hydroperoxy group at positions 12 has S-configuration.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of alvocidib.

A hydrochloride salt resulting from the formal reaction of equimolar amounts of alvocidib and hydrogen chloride. A cyclin-dependent kinase 9 (CDK9) inhibitor, it has been studied for the treatment of acute myeloid leukaemia, arthritis and atherosclerotic plaque formation.
An organic sodium salt having 3alpha,7alpha-dihydroxy-5beta-cholane-24-sulfonate as the counterion.
An icosanoid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of resolvin E1; major species at pH 7.3.
An icosanoid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of 18-oxoresolvin E1; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of sucrose 6(G)-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
Any of the organic heteropolycyclic quinazolinone alkaloid mycotoxins originally isolated from the fungus Aspergillus alliaceus. The term also includes their semi-synthetic and synthetic analogues.
A D-glucopyranose 6-phosphate(2-) resulting from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of D-galactopyranose 6-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-[(E)-caffeoyl]shikimic acid. Major structure at pH 7.3
A vitamin D that is 19-norcalcitriol carrying an additional 3-hydroxypropyl substituent at position 2. A synthetic analogue of vitamin D, it exhibits anticancer properties.
A carboxylic acic anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any aromatic carboxylic acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
A member of the class of pterocarpans that is 3-hydroxy-9,10-dimethoxypterocarpan in which the phenol hydrogen is replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
A 2,3-dichloromuconic acid in which both double bonds have Z geochemistry.
A 2,3-dichloromuconate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of (2Z,4Z)-2,3-dichloromuconic acid. Major species at pH 7.3

A member of the class of enamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-benzamido-3-phenylprop-2-enoic acid with the aromatic amino group of 2-[(4-aminophenyl)sulfanyl]propanoic acid, the carboxy group of which has also undergone formal condensation with the amino group of 5-chloro-2,4-dimethoxyaniline.
An organophosphate oxoanion resulting from the deprotonation of all four phosphate OH groups from D-ribose 5-triphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of mersacidin. Major species at pH 7.3.
A chemical compound that, when added to a liquid or gas, decreases the corrosion rate of a material, typically a metal or an alloy.
A GABA receptor agonist specific for GABAA receptors, ligand-gated ion channels (also known as ionotropic receptors).

Trisporic acids are C-18 terpenoid compounds consisting of (1S)-1,3-dimethyl-4-oxocyclohex-2-ene-1-carboxylic acid which is substituted at position 3 by a (1E-3-methylocta-1,3-dien-1-yl side chain. The double bond at position 3 of the side chain can have E or Z geometry. Position 7 of the side chain may be unsubstituted (trisporic acid A) or substituted by a hydroxy group (trisporic acid B) or an oxo group (trisporic acid C). The trisporic acids are synthesized via beta-carotene and retinol pathways in the Zygomycetes and are pheromone compounds responsible for sexual differentiation in those fungal species.
